FrantzFanon2000, thank you very much for your genuinely helpful comment. I believe there is a misunderstanding. Esra Albayrak forwarded the e-mails to her husband Berat, who is a minister. In other words, Esra Albayrak's e-mail account was not hacked. She chose to share the documents with a third party who was not even affiliated with UC Berkeley. According to your explanation, the FERPA protection over Mahmood's e-mails because they were obtained from the student's e-mail account should be irrelevant. Is that correct? Also, Esra Albayrak is a public figure who was serving on boards of major  national organizations at the time. I would be happy to write a brief biographical entry on her if you think that would be helpful. Once again, thank you so much!
Changed the place of a section.

The section is not under "Overview of Work," it is a separate section. You can refer to any substantial biography for comparable examples. The text is not altered at all, except for tense and personal pronouns--which are properly indicated in brackets. If you could clearly explain what is "speculative" in this objective (whatever that means) description of the contents of a primary source, I would be delighted to revise it. Unfortunately, repeatedly and libelously describing the content of the paragraph as "speculative" does not immediately create the truth effect you desire for all parties involved.

Could you please explain what interpretation you believe the paragraph to be making? The information only describes the content of a widely known and publicly available material. It does not even claim that the text mentioned is valid. Even if you perceive the primary source to be speculative, for whatever reason of your own, the paragraph does not make any claim about Mahmood's person, politics or work based on that supposedly speculative material. It simply explains the content of a widely known text attributed to Mahmood, which she never rejected.

The section is not in violation of the rule cited (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:No_original_research#Primary,_secondary_and_tertiary_sources). The rule does not prohibit the use of primary sources. There is no reference to Wikileaks as an unacceptable source. Finally, the paragraph does not make an interpretive claim based on the primary source. It only gives the necessary historical context for the reader to understand why "that past year" had been hard for Turkey, with links to relevant Wikipedia pages.
/* Career */ Provided explanation for a paragraph on Mahmood that has been deleted multiple times.

Added a section on the Wikileaks material on Mahmood. The material is not "gossip" and sources are provided. The reference to public debates were not made to make an argument for validity, they were cited as evidence of relevance. If you need sources that can help you improve your reading comprehension skills, I would be delighted to be of assistance. Moreover, Facebook posts and other social media material are used by humanities and social science scholars worldwide to follow social trends and public debates. Please do not hesitate to write if you need a reading list. Moreover, there is an enormous amount of "actual gossip" on Wikipedia, you are welcome to read almost any biography concerning any celebrity to confirm. The political debate was meant to explain the relevance of the added material. If it is unclear, I am happy to discuss the issue in further detail.

/* Wikileaks */ I doubt how anyone can determine whether an information is of "limited to nonexistent historical or political interest," given the diversity of material available on Wikipedia. To many Turkish scholars suffering under the Erdogan regime and their allies, as well as others in the Middle East, this issue is immensely important--not because it shows Mahmood's personal politics but rather because it demonstrates the concrete forms her line of thinking can take. Hence we perceive the event as part of her heritage. Also, to clarify, the citation is not from a student e-mail. It is from an e-mail by a professor. As far as I know, FERPA actually discourages professors from sending information concerning educational records via e-mail since they can be accessed by third parties, legally and illegally. (http://psych.fullerton.edu/mbirnbaum/psych101/grades_by_email.htm) Can you recommend sources that explicitly state all e-mails by professors to students are protected under FERPA?

Added a section on the Wikileaks material on Mahmood, which created controversy in Middle East studies circles. The ongoing debates on social media venues after Mahmood's death show that this issue is not off-topic at all. The paragraph only cites the text and gives the context, and says nothing libelous about Mahmood's character, politics or the quality of her work. Nor does the paragraph use the illegally obtained material as evidence to make any such claim. If citing material protected by FERPA is against the Wikipedia rules, I would kindly ask the users to cite the relevant rule instead of making libelous, speculative, smearing, and bizzare claims about my user profile or the text.

There is lots of information about Saba Mahmood over the internet, none of which relate to what is at stake in this reference, which demonstrate the non-relevance of the "facts" here.
